{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"651cde7a-1ff2-416d-aaf7-fd9db04c5afb","content":"Here's a streamlined approach for tracing .NET 8 in a Windows container on K8s:\n\n**1. Get a shell into the container:**\n```bash\nkubectl exec -it <pod-name> -- powershell\n```\n\n**2. Install `dotnet-trace` (if not already present):**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-trace\n```\n\n**3. Find your process ID:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace ps\n```\n\n**4. Collect a CPU trace:**\n```powershell\ndotnet-trace collect -p <PID> --profile cpu-sampling --duration 00:00:30\n```\n\nThis writes a `.nettrace` file you can analyze in **Visual Studio** or **PerfView**.\n\n**To get the file off the pod:**\n```bash\nkubectl cp <pod>:<path-to-nettrace> ./trace.nettrace\n```\n\n**Alternative — `dotnet-counters` for a quick look first:**\n```powershell\ndotnet tool install --global dotnet-counters\ndotnet-counters monitor -p <PID> --counters System.Runtime\n```\nThis gives live CPU %, GC, thread-pool stats — useful to confirm the problem before collecting a full trace.\n\n> **Tip:** If the container lacks the .NET SDK, you can sidecar or copy the standalone `dotnet-trace` tool in. Also, if `kubectl exec` isn't available, use `crictl` on the host node with your admin access to exec into the container directly.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"76c63c72-0b38-415f-a125-03f221bad0a6","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking for guidance on collecting a performance trace from a .NET 8 application running in a Windows container on Kubernetes, where they're experiencing high CPU. This is a troubleshooting/diagnostic question, not a code change request. I'll provide concise guidance.","outputTokens":436,"requestId":"D7C6:100995:EBBD12:10DCE71:69F2AF3E"},"id":"e77bc380-5dac-4245-b718-b11e82299da8","timestamp":"2026-04-30T01:24:26.846Z","parentId":"8d806a26-f82e-4146-856a-f0320775d570"}
